NBA Players Return

By Connor O’Rourke

With the new NBA season starting up and now going into full swing, there’s debate over whether it’s better to develop you’re own team or trade for them.

So here’s a study on what’s been better for each team and overall.

What I did was I returned each player to where their pick is from.

A simple example is the Luka Doncic for Tre Young trade.
- In this, Luka would be on the Hawks and Tre would be on the Mavericks.

A more nuanced situation is the Celtics and Nets picks saga.
- Jaylen Brown will be on the Nets as you see.
- Jayson Tatum isn’t actually on either team, as I’ll explain this weird situation later.

How I will construct each team:
1. I took the 9-11 man rotation of each team and wrote down their original picks.
2. I then created a starting rotation and 4 bench players.
3. If a team doesn’t have 9 players, I replace the empty spot with Anthony Bennett’s rookie season (his worst season).

What this season looks like:

You may ask if this qualifies for cruel and unusual punishment. As for unusual it definitely is but in my opinion is justified, as if you can’t get 9 players from your picks that play meaningful minutes the remaining spots are busts like Bennett.

As for cruel, let’s break it down.

How bad was Anthony Bennett

This may be a bit off-tangent but I thought it was very funny to see, I honestly didn’t think it was this bad.

To start, I’ll be comparing 2014 Anthony Bennett to players from the 2021-2022 NBA Season, as that was the most recent full season when this study was done.

Player Efficiency Rating (PER)

PER looks at how efficient a player is on a per minute basis. It takes all the positives they do offensively and defensively and subtracts any negatives. Although it can’t really take into account perceived defensive skill, it’s a simple way to show how effective a player is.

shortened = rbind(players_2022[players_2022$countGames >= 50,], goat)
worst_per = shortened[order(shortened$ratioPER),]
bottom_6 = head(worst_per, 6)

ggplot(bottom_6, aes(reorder(namePlayer, ratioPER), ratioPER))+
  geom_bar(aes(fill=grepl("Anthony Bennett", namePlayer)), stat="identity") +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  ggtitle("Worst PER of players with 50+ games in 2022 and 2014 Anthony Bennett") + 
  labs(y = "PER", x = "Player")

Here, Anthony Bennett would’ve been the second worst player in the NBA, only above washed up Tony Snell who’s most known for having 0 0 0 and 0 in 24 minutes, and slightly behind [REDACTED].

True Shooting Percentage (TS%)

True Shooting Percentage takes shooting percentage, and weights it based on how valuable a shot is. This means you’re shooting percentage on 3s is increased and free throw percentage is weighed differently.

I’ll quickly skip over some repeat code now aside from the parts with changed stats.

worst_tsp = shortened[order(shortened$pctTrueShooting),]
ggplot(bottom_6, aes(reorder(namePlayer, pctTrueShooting), pctTrueShooting))+
  geom_bar(aes(fill=grepl("Anthony Bennett", namePlayer)), stat="identity") +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  ggtitle("Worst TS% of players with 50+ games in 2022 and 2014 Anthony Bennett") + 
  labs(y = "TS%", x = "Player")

The only person below Anthony Bennett here is Elfrid Payton, who had a season shooting wise I didn’t even think was possible. As a guard, he shot 38.3% from the field, 22.2% from 3, and had a free throw percentage of 37.5%.

Win Shares

Win shares takes a player’s value and puts it into the number of wins (or losses) contributed to a team.

worst_ws = shortened[order(shortened$ratioWS),]
ggplot(bottom_6, aes(reorder(namePlayer, ratioWS), ratioWS))+
  geom_bar(aes(fill=grepl("Anthony Bennett", namePlayer)), stat="identity") +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  ggtitle("Lowest Win Shares of players with 50+ games in 2022 and 2014 Anthony Bennett") + 
  labs(y = "Win Shares", x = "Player")

The first thing is that having negative win shares is really bad. Like with negative win shares the team wins more when you’re not on the team. This also doesn’t have Jalen Suggs shown, who despite only playing 48 games had a whopping -1.6 win shares.

Win Shares Per 48 Minutes

This just takes win shares and puts it on an equal per game basis to make up for players that play more.

worst_wsper48 = shortened[order(shortened$ratioWSPer48),]
ggplot(bottom_6, aes(reorder(namePlayer, ratioWSPer48), ratioWSPer48))+
  geom_bar(aes(fill=grepl("Anthony Bennett", namePlayer)), stat="identity") +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  ggtitle("Lowest Win Shares Per 48 Minutes of players with 50+ games in 2022 and 2014 Anthony Bennett") + 
  labs(y = "Win Shares Per 48 Minutes", x = "Player")

Here we see Anthony Bennett truly shine. Even though he looks around the same as Cade Cunningham, a bright young NBA talent, putting it on a per-rate basis shows Bennett is by far the worst player in the NBA. Bennett is twice as bad as the next worst player, Elfrid Payton.

Value Over Replacement Player (VORP)

VORP estimates the amount of box score points a player contributes to a team over a replacement level player, which is -2.0 VORP.

worst_vorp = shortened[order(shortened$ratioVORP),]
ggplot(bottom_6, aes(reorder(namePlayer, ratioVORP), ratioVORP))+
  geom_bar(aes(fill=grepl("Anthony Bennett", namePlayer)), stat="identity") +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  ggtitle("Lowest VORP of players with 50+ games in 2022 and 2014 Anthony Bennett") + 
  labs(y = "Value Over Replacement Player", x = "Player")

Luckily all players here are better than replacement level, but again Anthony Bennett is near the bottom of the bottom 6 players.

Final Verdict

Anthony Bennett was in at best the bottom 2 of the main advanced stats in the NBA among players with at least 50 games, making him in my opinion easily the worst player in the NBA if he were in the 2021-2022 season. Due to this, I would consider the Anthony Bennett rule cruel and unusual punishment, but let’s see how each team fairs.

How Winning Percentage For Each New Team Is Calculated

Before the fun we need to cover more nerd shit.

Discussion: Scientific Flaws and Methodology

Do I recommend reading this if you’re not a stats nerd or you had no issues with how I calculated wins, no, but if any of those two things applied to you here’s this information in a Q&A format.

Why Win Shares?

I Initially wanted to calculate the points for and against for each NBA team then use pythagorean wins, but I realized it would be very difficult to interpret a player’s value on a new team with a new system. It’s not like sports like baseball where players can feel very plug and play, some players just don’t work well together in the NBA. A roster of the best 3-point shooters at each position, although valuable at face value, wouldn’t mesh well together on the court. This is why I decided to use win shares, as it’s a simple interpretation of a player’s “value.”

Why use last year instead of what has happened this year?

This one is pretty simple. Only 20-30 something games have happened so far this year. We’re not even half way in and a lot can happen. A player can get injured for the rest of the season (See: AD, Cade or Curry), or just get worse as the season goes on. If I look at last year, I get a full season to interpret stats. But even then there’s some other small issues I’ll touch on:
1. Players that missed the whole season. - Although this deflates their stats it’s something important to consider for their value year on year given their injury prone-ness.
2. Rookies for this season. - Something I should’ve accounted for, as rookies in my study acted as a new player instead of still being on their original teams, though this didn’t have too much of an effect in my opinion as it only effected a few teams and most rookies tend to have very low win shares, barely affecting the totals.
3. Projecting players for the 2023 season. - This one is fully on me, as I interpreted a player’s 2023 value as if they played 82 games, which isn’t realistic, instead of taking the proportion of games they’ve played to far and projecting it to a 82 games season.

How Did You Choose the Rotations You Did?

It was all personal decision, I was the head coach for each team. I tried to look at most minutes played to affect bench as well, but simply taking the 9 most valuable players would be unfair, as that’s not what I did for the original teams. I also didn’t want to take the 9 most played players in favor of starting a known player like Dame that was hurt all last year, as I thought it should be taken into account.
